<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910424-0205</DOCNO><DOCID>910424-0205.</DOCID><HL>   Politics andamp; Policy:   Hospital to Honor Reagan   10 Years After Shooting</HL><DATE>03/21/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><IN>HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)</IN><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Almost 10 years from the day he was shot bya would-be assassin, former President Reagan will return toGeorge Washington University Hospital to mark the event.   Both the president and press secretary James Brady wererushed to the hospital's emergency room after they werewounded by John Hinckley on March 30, 1981. On Mr. Reagan'sMarch 28 return visit, the university's hospital willdedicate a new Ronald Reagan Institute for EmergencyMedicine, and the university will present him with anhonorary doctorate for public service.</LP><TEXT>   In the years since the shooting, Mr. Brady has led forcesseeking stricter handgun controls. Mr. Reagan, a lifetimemember of the National Rifle Association, generally opposesstricter controls.</TEXT></DOC>